# PowerShell Shell Rules

This workspace uses PowerShell. Bash syntax does not work.

## Git commits

- NEVER use heredoc (`<<'EOF'`) for commit messages - PowerShell does not support it
- Use single-line `-m "message"` for commits
- For multi-line messages, write to a temp file first:
  ```powershell
  Set-Content -Path .git\COMMIT_MSG -Value "Title`n`nBody here"
  git commit -F .git\COMMIT_MSG
  Remove-Item .git\COMMIT_MSG
  ```

## npm scripts (package.json)

npm scripts run via `cmd.exe` on Windows, not PowerShell or bash. They must be cross-platform:

- NEVER use `test -d`, `true`, `false`, `grep`, `sed`, `awk`, `which`, `chmod`, `ln -s`, or other Unix-only commands
- For conditional logic, use `node -e` with inline JavaScript instead
- Example: `"postinstall": "node -e \"try{require('fs').statSync('dir/package.json');require('child_process').execSync('npm install',{cwd:'dir',stdio:'inherit'})}catch(e){}\""` 

## No em dashes or special Unicode

- NEVER use em dashes (`—`, U+2014) or en dashes (`–`, U+2013) in `.ps1` files or any string that will be written to a `.ps1` file
- PowerShell 5.1 reads scripts as ANSI (Windows-1252) by default; multi-byte UTF-8 characters like em dashes corrupt the parser and cause silent script failures
- Use a plain hyphen-minus (`-`) instead

## Other reminders

- Use `Select-Object -First N` instead of `head -N`
- Use `Select-Object -Last N` instead of `tail -N`
- Use PowerShell here-strings (`@"..."@`) instead of bash heredocs if multi-line input is needed
- Chain commands with `&&` (PowerShell 7+) or `;` - not `\` for line continuation
